<subSubSection box="[151,537,1297,1323]" pageId="2" pageNumber="175" type="nomenclature">
<paragraph blockId="2.[151,537,1297,1323]" box="[151,537,1297,1323]" pageId="2" pageNumber="175">
<heading bold="true" box="[151,537,1297,1323]" fontSize="11" level="1" pageId="2" pageNumber="175" reason="1">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,537,1297,1323]" pageId="2" pageNumber="175">
Genus 
<taxonomicName authority="Krauss 1911" authorityName="Krauss" authorityYear="1911" box="[238,537,1297,1323]" class="Insecta" family="Oligotomidae" genus="Aposthonia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Embioptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="175" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[238,377,1297,1323]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="175">Aposthonia</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation box="[384,537,1297,1323]" pageId="2" pageNumber="175" refId="ref4818" refString="Krauss, H. A. (1911) Monographie der Embien. Zoologica, Stuttgart, 23, 1 - 78." type="journal article">Krauss 1911</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="2" pageNumber="175" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="2.[151,1437,1367,1645]" pageId="2" pageNumber="175">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,273,1367,1392]" pageId="2" pageNumber="175">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
Resembles 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Westwood" authorityYear="1837" box="[420,540,1368,1392]" class="Insecta" family="Oligotomidae" genus="Oligotoma" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Embioptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="175" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[420,540,1368,1392]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="175">Oligotoma</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
except for the absence of the mesad lobe of the LCB and the simple left paraproct process (LPPT). Differs from 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Ross" authorityYear="2007" box="[600,710,1404,1428]" class="Insecta" family="Oligotomidae" genus="Eosembia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Embioptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="175" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[600,710,1404,1428]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="175">Eosembia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by the presence of single papillae on the hind basitarsus, narrow LP and inconspicuous aedeagus.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection box="[199,519,1476,1501]" pageId="2" pageNumber="175" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="2.[151,1437,1367,1645]" box="[199,519,1476,1501]" pageId="2" pageNumber="175">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,352,1476,1501]" pageId="2" pageNumber="175">Distribution.</emphasis>
Tropical Asia.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="2" pageNumber="175" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="2.[151,1437,1367,1645]" pageId="2" pageNumber="175">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,315,1511,1536]" pageId="2" pageNumber="175">Remarks.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName authorityName="Krauss" authorityYear="1911" box="[322,449,1512,1536]" class="Insecta" family="Oligotomidae" genus="Aposthonia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Embioptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="175" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[322,449,1512,1536]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="175">Aposthonia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is one of the largest and widely distributed genera. It is probably a polyphyletic group, serving as a “catch-all” genus for 
<taxonomicName authority="(Ross 2007)" authorityName="Ross" authorityYear="2007" baseAuthorityName="Ross" baseAuthorityYear="2007" box="[550,857,1548,1573]" class="Insecta" family="Oligotomidae" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Embioptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="175" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">
Oligotomidae (
<bibRefCitation box="[722,849,1548,1572]" pageId="2" pageNumber="175" refId="ref5825" refString="Ross, E. S. (2007) The Embiidina of Eastern Asia, Part 1. Proceedings of the California Academy of Sciences, 58 (29), 575 - 600." type="journal article">Ross 2007</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
. This is supported in cladistic analysis of 
<bibRefCitation pageId="2" pageNumber="175" refId="ref5909" refString="Szumik, C. (1996) The higher classification of the order Embioptera: A cladistic analysis. Cladistics, 12, 41 - 64." type="journal article">Szumik (1996)</bibRefCitation>
and 
<bibRefCitation box="[283,504,1583,1608]" pageId="2" pageNumber="175" refId="ref5002" refString="Miller, K. B., Hayashi, C., Whiting, M. F., Svenson, G. J. &amp; Edgerly, J. S. (2012) The phylogeny and classification of Embioptera (Insecta). Systematic Entomology, 37, 550 - 570. https: // doi. org / 10.1111 / j. 1365 - 3113.2012.00628. x" type="journal article">Miller et al. (2012)</bibRefCitation>
. 
<bibRefCitation box="[516,654,1584,1608]" pageId="2" pageNumber="175" refId="ref5825" refString="Ross, E. S. (2007) The Embiidina of Eastern Asia, Part 1. Proceedings of the California Academy of Sciences, 58 (29), 575 - 600." type="journal article">Ross (2007)</bibRefCitation>
reported that the Philippine diversity of webspinners was comprised mainly of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Krauss" authorityYear="1911" box="[266,393,1620,1644]" class="Insecta" family="Oligotomidae" genus="Aposthonia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Embioptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="175" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[266,393,1620,1644]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="175">Aposthonia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, a genus common in the Indo-Australian region.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
